{"amendments":[{"body":"`src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs:415-447` and `src/adapters/fs.rs:2760-2774` let `record_task_run_start` reuse a lone runless open row even when another named run for the same bead/project is already open. In a mixed legacy state like `(run_id=None, outcome=running)` plus `(run_id=\"run-2\", outcome=running)`, starting `run-3` returns `Ok(())` and rewrites the runless row to `run-3`, leaving two simultaneous open attempts for the same bead/project. I reproduced this with a small harness against the current code. That corrupts lineage attribution instead of surfacing the state as ambiguous; the start path should reject this mixed-open case the same way `update_task_run` already does.","rationale":"This is a real robustness bug in the new lineage logic: a malformed or partially migrated task-runs file can be silently rewritten into a different attempt history."},{"body":"`src/adapters/fs.rs:2648-2657` and `src/adapters/fs.rs:3015-3020` silently ignore a conflicting `plan_hash` once a running row already has any hash. I reproduced a normal start/completion flow where `record_bead_start(..., plan_hash=\"plan-v1\")` is followed by `record_bead_completion(..., plan_hash=\"plan-v2\")`; the call succeeds, but the persisted `TaskRunEntry` still reports `plan_hash=\"plan-v1\"`. Because the whole point of this task is to audit which plan/run attempted a bead, returning success while dropping the caller's newer hash produces incorrect milestone lineage data. The update path should either reject conflicting hashes or explicitly overwrite them.","rationale":"This breaks the new audit field directly: callers can believe they recorded the final plan hash, but the stored lineage remains stale."}],"summary":"Reviewed the milestone-record changes by diffing against `8b3e0c3`, reading the updated model/service/FS adapter code, and running `cargo test milestone_record -- --nocapture` (all passing). I found two correctness gaps that are not covered by the current tests: one ambiguous-start path that can relabel a legacy open row, and one plan-hash update path that reports success while preserving stale lineage metadata."}